node.title: ParsedFunction erroring out on cluster
node.bodyText:
Hi,
I have the expression
  [./pulse1]
    type = ParsedFunction
    vars = 't0 t1 A'
    vals = '0.0 100.0 0.707107'
    value = 'if(t < t1, A*0.1*(sin(10.0*(z-30.0))/(10.0*(z-30.0)))*sin(1e6*(t-1e-6))/(1e6*(t-1e-6)), if(t > t1, 0.0, 0.0))'
  [../]


which works just fine on my local box. However, the cluster complains:
ERROR: FunctionParser is unable to evaluate component 0 for 'f' of expression 'if(t < t1, A*0.07*(sin(10.0*(z-30.0))/(10.0*(z-30.0)))*sin(1e6*(t-1e-6))/(1e6*(t-1e-6)), if(t > t1, 0.0, 0.0))' with arguments:
        0
        0
        30
        0
        0
        100
        0.707107

What could be going wrong here?

Seems to be an issue with dividing by zero. But sinc(x) is defined at 0... Is there a sinc(x) function I can use for ParsedFunction? I tried this to no luck.
Also, this was working a few weeks ago and encountered it without updating MOOSE on the cluster. But a new update does not change this error. I removed the if statements to test,
  [./pulse1]
    type = ParsedFunction
    value = '0.707107*0.1*((sin(10.0*z-300.0)/(10.0*z-300.0))*(sin(1e6*t-1)/(1e6*t-1)))'
  [../]

also tried to change the order of operations here   value = '(0.707107/(10.0*z-300.0))*(0.1/(1e6*t-1))*(sin(10.0*z-300.0)*sin(1e6*t-1))'
and still get the issue.

iirc this is the docs for fparser
http://warp.povusers.org/FunctionParser/fparser.html
I dont see sinc() in there.
so you're hitting the issue with z=30 or t = 1e-6 ?
I suppose the first one.

I saw sinc() only exists in Boost.
Seems the spatial coordinate is causing it to diverge but it is strange because when I have sin(k*(z-z0))/(k*(z-z0)) on my local linux box, everything is fine (see attached timestep 1).

I think the parser just doesnt like to see the division by 0.
If I were you I d define the function in two parts using an if statement

away from 0, this definition
near 0, a high order Taylor expansion which removes the division by 0
Sure, but why does the cluster (using ./scripts/build_libmesh to compile) performs differently than the conda libmesh env?
Could be different optimization flags @milljm will know

@milljm @cticenhour any idea on why we can get different FPException behavior between those two platforms & build methods?
It might not be that, I m guessing here

node.title: Can not build  a phase field app

node.bodyText:
Hello
this looks like the versions of libmesh and moose are not in sync.
how are you installing moose? With the conda installation?
If so, could you please report the output of conda list for the moose packages?
And which moose commit are you using?
Guillaume

Hello Guillaume,
Thanks for the reply. I am installing moose in the following way-
conda deactivate
conda env remove -n moose
conda config --remove channels idaholab
conda config --add channels https://conda.software.inl.gov/public
conda create --name moose -q -y
conda activate moose
conda install gxx_linux-64
conda install -c anaconda git
conda install moose-tools
conda install moose-libmesh
git clone https://github.com/idaholab/moose.git
git checkout master
make -j 4
Then I downloaded the app as mentioned earlier and tried to build it with " make -j 4 "

Be sure to deactivate and reactivate the environment after installing the packages:
conda install moose-tools
conda install moose-libmesh
conda deactivate
conda activate moose
The reason for this, is that there are initialization scripts that must be executed after the installation of moose-libmesh (and others).
I was never a fan of our previous instructions specifying the creation of an empty environment, enter it, install packages, leave it, enter it again 🙄 ...Of course, we were doing it this way back then due to how slow 'conda install' was. If you're still using 'conda' I suppose you'll want to keep doing what you're doing. But my advice is to install mamba (conda install mamba), and then use that. Mamba works exactly like conda. The only thing mamba can't do, are the config subcommands (conda config --add channel etc).
We have updated our instructions to be a bit more clean moving forward:
mamba create -n moose moose-libmesh moose-tools
mamba activate moose
With that all out of the way, I take it the issue persists? The same exact issue? I've seen this index_range error before, recently. What operating system are you working in by chance?

node.title: Kernel variables
node.bodyText:
Dear MOOSE experts,
I am very new to MOOSE and want to model convection flow (for phase field model). I have followed Example 2 and Example 8, but my problem is that variable u in v ⋅∇u is a function of other variables. In this case, how should I define u in ex02.i? Any help would be appreciated.
Kinds,
Jung

Take a look at Example 3: In short, you'll create multiple kernels for your terms in your "u" and "v" equations. If you have a term where both variables appear (i.e. v ⋅∇u), you'll use the "coupling" capability to pull in values from the other variable for use in calculating your term
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/getting_started/examples_and_tutorials/examples/ex03_coupling.html

bin.txt
lib.txt

It looks like Homebrew is installed.
The issue is, Homebrew installs one profile to the machine, in a location which is always active. The dependencies MOOSE requires, such as libMesh for example will search and find things like BOOST in hard-coded locations like /usr/local/lib. The unfortunate side effect of doing so, is that it will also include any other libraries it finds in this location... including that other implementation of MPI I see:
lrwxr-xr-x    1 user  admin    44B  9 Jan  2020 libmpi.40.dylib -> ../Cellar/open-mpi/4.0.2/lib/libmpi.40.dylib
lrwxr-xr-x    1 user  admin    41B  9 Jan  2020 libmpi.dylib -> ../Cellar/open-mpi/4.0.2/lib/libmpi.dylib
There are some solutions available. Some can get complex, some might be easy. According to this post: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42859781/best-practices-with-anaconda-and-brew, these folks are displaying ways of using both.
My advice for novice users (not saying you are one 😄!), is to only use one or the other.

node.title: AD

node.bodyText:
Just another question here again.
pressure is a real value and velocity is vector value, right?
the following statement is correct or not?
_p(adCoupledValue("pressure")),
_grad_p(adCoupledGradient("pressure"))
After taking the gradient of pressure, _grad_p will become as a vector value, right?
then if I treat gradient of pressure as the coupled value, it will become as follows, am I right?
_grad_p(adCoupledVectorValue("_grad_p"))
Thanks again.

No you can’t do that because grad_p is not a variable name.
ADCoupledGradient is getting you the gradient of a variable, and storing it as a vector
Thanks a lot, I see your point.

node.title: Do we have a spatial gradient in material?
node.bodyText:
Hi,
I can see there is adCoupledVectorGradient for coupled variable. Do we also have something similar when we want to retrieve the spatial gradients of some properties from material?
Thank you.
Regards,
Qiao

Not that I know of but you can easily compute it and define it yourself.
If you’re just running through the tutorial and need some guidance no need to post in several places by the way
Ok, I see. thanks

So I see there might be some problems in Jacobian, leading to not converging of my code, but I don't know the meaning of the messages and what I can do to fix the problem, can anybody tell me about how to debug based on the messages of jacobiananalizer?

Thank you so much!

Hello
These messages say that the Jacobian is not fully implemented for the off-diagonal terms and that you may be missing some dependences in the diagonal term as well.
You need to re-derive the Jacobian and implement the missing terms.
Alternatively, you can switch your work to using automatic differentiation. This computes a perfect numerical Jacobian.
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/automatic_differentiation/#!
Guillaume
PS: there are also some caveats to the Jacobian analyzer. Make sure you followed the instructions for its use exactly otherwise it ll detect false positives

Thanks！ I also want to know if there is any way to compute condition number of the matrix.

Hello
yes you may use:
petsc_options_iname = '-pc_type'
petsc_options_ivalue = 'svd'
petsc_options = -pc_svd_monitor

this is really slow, use it only with a few thousands dofs at most
Guillaume

node.title: Questions about the kernel(MatDiffusion).
node.bodyText:
Dear MOOSE experts,
In this article (Zijian Hong, Venkatasubramanian Viswanathan. Phase-Field simulations of lithium dendrite growth with open-source software. ACS Energy Lett., 2018, 3, 7, 1737–1743), the author has compiled a kernel(Migration). But I think it's OK to use the original kernel(MatDiffusion). Then I tried to simulate, but the result was different from the original. Can you help me see the difference between the two kernels?
Thank you.
Original file input.i
[Kernels]
  [./Diffusion2]
    # Migration.
    type = Migration
    variable = w
    cv = eta
    Q_name = 0.
    QM_name = DN
    cp = pot
  [../]

I modified input.i
  [./Diffusion2]
    # Originally Migration, I changed it to MatDiffusion.
    type = MatDiffusion
    variable = pot
    diffusivity = DN
    args = 'eta w'
  [../]

[Materials]
  [./Migration_coefficient]
    # Migration coefficient.
    type = DerivativeParsedMaterial
    function = '-cl*(1-h)*AA*M0*(1-h)'
    args = 'eta w'
    f_name = DN
    derivative_order = 1
    material_property_names = 'M0 AA cl:=D[f1,w] h'
  [../]

Migration.txt

Hello
The residual term is different.
Your input, roughly:
grad_v[_qp] * _grad_test[_i][_qp] * -cl*(1-h)*AA*M0*(1-h)
Theirs:
_Q[_qp]*_grad_cv[_qp]*_grad_test[_i][_qp]+_QM[_qp]*_grad_cp[_qp]*_grad_test[_i][_qp];
It seems you are missing a second variable
I'd encourage you to output the equivalent of the diffusion coefficient in the original simulation and see if you can reproduce that with your material.
Guillaume

Hello
What is the function of the v in the kernel（MatDiffusion）? I read the instructions on the website, but I didn't understand  where v works. Can you give me an example?
Thank you.
It s to couple another variable than the variable attached to the equation (usually the one featured in the time derivative)

Hi Wei, I don't have time to dive into this right now, but what I typically due to troubleshoot is to look at the solution (image) of the initial condition for the order parameter in question. Look to see if there are two grains that are exceptionally close (maybe just a few elements apart) that look like they may be close to contact. What can happen is when you start to solve the phase-field equations and those sharp interfaces start to diffuse, these grains can rapidly grow in just one time step. I haven't run into this very much (admittedly I've only dealt with a handful of real EBSD files so my sample size is also low).
The PolyCrystalInitialCondition system was designed with this scenario in mind. There is a "halo level" just for the IC that's baked into that class (I haven't exposed it as an input parameter, but you could change that value and recompile). The idea is that for these types of cases where we have two grains somewhat close to each other, we might be able to force the coloring algorithm to place them on different order parameters instead of placing them more closely by increasing that halo level (they'll intersect before being placed).
Other solutions would be to try a different coloring algorithm just to see if you get lucky by perturbing the layout of how the grains are assigned to OPs. The back-tracking algorithm (although potentially the slowest of these - with potential exponential runtime!) typically does the best of spreading out your grains more evenly than the stochastic algorithms in PETSc.
Feel free to post images of your IC here and also "order parameter 2". I'd be happy to guide you through fixing this and will help as I can!
